An American-style capitalism of favoritism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the US Treasury Department and its IMF allies blamed the problems in that region on a capitalism of favoritism, lack of transparency, and ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, to bring in American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It didn't matter that under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed more rapidly than any other region - and with greater stability - over the last three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be faultless to criticize others."
Enron used elaborate accounting strategies and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to acquire influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and evade regulations.
Favoritism-based capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of one party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, allegedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards-setting body attempted to clean up the accounting of executive bonuses.
It was in part due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was obstructed.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is merely a thin veil for the benefit of established businesses: giving to those who have the right connections.
To some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of favoritism-based capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it testifies to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to look into Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was revealed.
Campaign contributions were not simply matters of public interest, but were investments.
As with most of Enron's investments, everything worked well in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this company.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests capable of actually buying elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons concern economics, more specifically the economics of information.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals to be provided to allocate resources efficiently, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as positive a picture as possible.
The audit is intended to set limits on potential abuses.
But who will watch the watchers?
Who will control the account controllers?
We rely greatly on motivations.
Auditors desire to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and audit control brings about other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within audit firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of audits could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unsung hero of the debacle.
But audit firms and their corporate clients - which is no surprise, given the cabal that has developed - strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and audit activities.
What Levitt understood - and what the Enron debacle so clearly showed - is that motivations are important, but unregulated markets cannot themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new complicated financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to confuse.
Instead of facing the problems, corporate America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will claim that Enron is an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information they receive sufficiently reflects a company's economic situation.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of receiving these guarantees at the moment.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot count on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we find that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of such abuses becomes evident, new places for abuse are repeatedly created - take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commerce from investments.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated free markets.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
